But blender has no way to export each object as its own stl!! Now I wasn't going to export 90 different files by hand, so after cobbling together various bits of info I put together this script.  
To use it you have to save the file with the parts in first, open the script in blenders text editor. Highlight all the parts you want to export and then run script. It will save the files in the same directory as the .blend file.

description.text: Filament spool holder for the Printrbot Simple Metal 1403. Uses a short piece of 8mm linear rail as an axle, mounts on top of the Z axis rods.

I added a cross piece to mount to both Z rods for stability.  This is sized to fit the largest spool I've received from Monoprice. If you come across a larger one that doesn't fit, use the openscad source. Design was shrunk a bit to fit the print bed of the simple metal.   
I've added top caps which mount to the 8mm rail and slide on top of the forks. This keeps the rail from walking off the holder while printing. Two are included in the design, but I only used one. It is a tight fit to the rail, but should be easy to lift on and off and slide through the filament spool.  Previously I used electrical tape to hold the rail on. This is a bit more elegant.  
To print, I used RotY=270deg, RotZ=90 deg. Turn skirt off or it won't fit. I used 0.200mm layers and 25% infill.  My print had a bit of corner lift and warping on one end of the fork, but works just fine using a top cap.

description.text: The Sunhokey acrylic design has a major problem of shedding its fasteners, since they're all t-slot design. remixed_from.title: Adapter to use any SATA drive in Seagate FreeAgent GoFlex

title: Seagate GoFlex Dock Adapter for 2.5" Hard Disk Drives

description.text:
The Seagate Free Agent GoFlex Docks were an excellent product, allowing interchange of hard disk drives and connectivity protocols. They made USB 3, FireWire, and even NAS docks for these hard disk drives. But the connector is standard SATA and could be used with any drive. That's where this adapter comes in.  
Use this adapter to connect any 2.5" laptop hard disk drive to a Seagate GoFlex dock. It supports the weight of the drive and reduces stress on the connectors. The adapter supports drives up to 15 mm in height (thickness) so just about any drive should work. It supports both generations of GoFlex desktop docks.  
I also created a "wedge" that adds extra support for drives under 15 mm. Just insert the drive, then snap in the wedge. Each "step" of the wedge matches one of the various drive heights: 12.5 mm, 9.5 mm, 7 mm, and 5 mm. And the wedge snaps into the adapter for storage!  
Although this was inspired by Symonty's "Adapter to use any SATA drive in Seagate FreeAgent GoFlex", I ended up designing this completely from scratch. I did list this as a remix for that adapter as a way of saying thanks for the inspiration!

description.text:
This is a remix of the 'Jurassic Park Gate "What do they have in there King Kong" by Drussell19.  
I took his original model and added some hinges, this required me to also widen the entrance. I created a LEGO® base and cleaned up the original STL to make it 3d printing friendly as the original model wouldn't slice correctly.

3d Print all of the individual parts and assemble as per the expanded photo. I had to split the base into 3 parts as it was too big to print on my printers bed, use the joining piece to hold the base together and glue (I used hot-melt glue). I finished it off by painting the pillars with a stone effect spray paint, the gates themselves were sprayed in brown, the text was hand painted in yellow and red. I added fine stone ballast (used for railway modelling) to make the road through the gates. More photos and info on my website

Print, assemble, play! The files contain the "v2.5"; The laying knobs and the smaller bars are easiest to remove and assemble.
The figures barely print, so making them larger would be a nice idea, but this would require a deeper play-box. You could print the handles on the bars, but as I am going to paint them anyway, they will just stick easily.
The first idea was to print the box without slot-in-holes, but this way it is much easier to assemble as the small figures would not print with a hole-through assembly. Painting over the open box with thick nail polish will shut those gaps (best to dry it upside down using a third hand holder), or you can simply glue a frame/bar over the gaps and then color it.
Another way would be the bigger bars which sort of snap in (perhaps make them yet a tad bigger and the box deeper so the figures can still turn)

description.text:
An universal cd-car phone holder. I designed it in order to change quickly the cradle from iPhone 5 to iPhone 6. You can create your own phone cradle and attach with glue the "Plate.stl" behind it. Update 23 Feb 2016:
Support2.0 is out!
• Better design, less plastic, less printing time
• Better architecture, now it's easier to slide the cradle in place Update 22 Sept 2015:
Now the "Support.stl" touch the build plate and it's easier to print.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3 Rework

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

100

I suggest printing it in ABS because exposed to the sun can melt
However, you can use PLA for both Support2.0 and Cradle and remember to remove the Cradle from the sun. You need:
• 1 x Support.stl
• As many Plates as Phone's cradles Just glue in place the "Plate.stl" behind the iPhone5, iPhone6 or your own cradle.
I suggest printing the "Support2.0.stl" at 100% infill
Enjoy!

FEEDERBOT
I made a filament rack and wanted to share the parts list and diagram so people could make their own. I spent a long while testing with spool sizes from all the usual suspects and this setup seems to work well with all.
The 3/4" pvc pipe (actual outer diameter 1" or 27mm) fits the smaller 33mm spools (Octave, MatterHackers) and the larger 52mm spools (MBI, Protoparadigm). One Note:
I sell this rack fully assembled and it includes the red threader cap that cleans the filament in some of the photos. Unfortunately since that part is patented I can't share it here. (http://www.feederbot.com)

3/4" PVC PIPE
You can use hardware store 3/4"PVC Schedule 40 pipe.
I use furniture grade PVC pipe - it's much more expensive but the high gloss finish produces very little friction when the spools are doing their thing. www.Lowes.com
www.Formufit.com I suggest dry fitting all pieces THEN use PVC pipe cement on all parts.
The cement dries in 30 seconds - so be careful with this step. In total you will need 1 x 10' length 3/4" PVC pipe cut down to:
1 x 15" (front foot)
1 x 10"
2 x 8"
4 x 7"
2 x 6"
2 x 5"
6 x 4" (5 of these are the spindles that the spools hang on)
2 x 1.5" 4 x 3-way elbow
5 x tee
1 x cross
3 x 90 degree elbows
5 end caps
